Cluster Analysis of Sexual Orientation

About Geovisualisations Technical Reports Python & Friends CV Contact

This is a cluster analysis of 2021 census data on sexual orientation, which shows which areas are statistical hotspots for people of different sexual identities.

The maps were calculated using local Moran's i (LISA) in Python.

London is an outlier in all cases, except for Asexuality, where is isn't significant at all.
Brighton is a massive hotspot for being Gay. So much so, that everything surrounding Brighton is a low-low cluster!

The map of people who refused to answer the question is perhaps a better measure of how openly people talk about sexuality. There is a huge swathe over the north of England where, statistically, fewer people refused to answer the question. This lines up with a large high-high cluster of people who answered 'Straight'.

The exception to this is Newcastle upon Tyne (the tiny orange dot in the sea of blue). Newcastle is a high-low cluster for Pansexuality, other sexualities, and refusing to answer.

This suggests that sexuality is a less divisive topic in the north of England.

Data Source: 2021 Census
